    "pathophysiology": "Hematogenous dissemination of primary tumor cells to liver via portal vein (GI primaries) or hepatic artery (non-GI primaries). Cells grow in hepatic parenchyma, compressing and displacing hepatocytes and bile ducts. Gradual replacement of functioning liver tissue leads to cholestasis from mass effect. Hilar lymph node metastases can cause large bile duct obstruction. Jaundice is often a late sign indicating significant parenchymal replacement or biliary obstruction.",
    "complications": [
